---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import marsLocations from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'olympus-mons');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Olympus Mons location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Olympus Mons - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-orange-900 to-red-900 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          The largest volcano in the solar system
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">Image: NASA/MOLA Science Team</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Olympus Mons stands as a colossal monument to Mars' volcanic past,
          rising as the tallest known volcano in our solar system. This massive
          shield volcano towers approximately 21.2 kilometers (13.2 miles) above
          the surrounding plains, nearly three times the height of Mount
          Everest. Its base spans roughly 600 kilometers (370 miles) in
          diameter, making it roughly the size of the state of Arizona.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Located in the Tharsis volcanic region, Olympus Mons formed over
          millions of years through repeated basaltic lava flows. The volcano's
          gentle slopes, averaging only 5 degrees, are characteristic of shield
          volcanoes formed by low-viscosity lava flows that spread over vast
          distances before cooling.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          What makes Olympus Mons particularly intriguing for future Mars
          exploration is its extensive network of lava tubes - natural
          underground tunnels that could serve as ready-made shelters for human
          habitats, protecting settlers from radiation, extreme temperatures,
          and dust storms.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Vital Statistics</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Height:</span>
            <span class="text-white">21.2 km (13.2 mi)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Base Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white">~600 km (370 mi)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Volume:</span>
            <span class="text-white">~300 million km³</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Last Activity:</span>
            <span class="text-white">20-200 million years ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Type:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Shield Volcano</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Geological Features -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Geological Features
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Volcanic Structure
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Olympus Mons exhibits a classic shield volcano profile with a large
          summit caldera complex measuring about 80 kilometers wide and up to 3
          kilometers deep. The caldera formed through repeated collapse events
          as magma chambers emptied during eruptions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The volcano's aureole, a distinctive scarp that surrounds the base,
          drops 2-8 kilometers to the surrounding plains. This feature may have
          formed through gravitational spreading of the massive volcanic pile or
          through interaction with underlying sediments.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Lava Tube Networks
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Extensive lava tube systems have been identified across Olympus Mons'
          flanks. These tubes formed when the outer surface of lava flows cooled
          and solidified while molten lava continued to flow beneath, eventually
          draining to leave hollow conduits.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          On Mars' lower gravity environment, these lava tubes can be
          significantly larger than their Earth counterparts - potentially up to
          several kilometers wide and hundreds of kilometers long.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Habitat Potential -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Lava Tubes as Human Habitats
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-r from-mars-900/40 to-gray-800/40 rounded-lg p-8 border border-mars-600"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Natural Protection Systems
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Lava tubes on Olympus Mons offer unparalleled natural protection for
          human settlements. The thick rock ceiling provides excellent shielding
          from cosmic radiation, solar radiation, and micrometeorite impacts.
          The stable internal environment maintains relatively constant
          temperatures year-round.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Radiation Shielding</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Meters of rock overhead block harmful cosmic rays and solar
              radiation that pose serious health risks on the surface.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Temperature Stability</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Interior temperatures remain stable, avoiding the extreme daily
              temperature swings experienced on the surface.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-700">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Atmospheric Protection
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Natural shelter from dust storms and the thin Martian atmosphere
              that provides little protection from space hazards.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
            Engineering Advantages
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Ready-made structures:</strong> No need to excavate or build
                pressure vessels from scratch</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Scalable expansion:</strong> Multiple connected tubes allow
                for modular habitat growth</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Structural integrity:</strong> Natural arches proven stable
                over millions of years</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Access points:</strong> Skylights and collapsed sections
                provide natural entrances</span
              >
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
            Resource Potential
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Volcanic materials:</strong> Rich in useful minerals for
                construction and manufacturing</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Water ice deposits:</strong> Potential ice accumulation
                in permanently shadowed areas</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Elevated position:</strong> Above much of the atmospheric
                dust for clear communications</span
              >
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-mars-orange mr-2">•</span>
              <span
                ><strong>Geothermal potential:</strong> Residual heat from the volcanic
                system</span
              >
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming and Settlement Assessment
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          With a terraforming rating of 8/10, Olympus Mons offers exceptional
          potential for human settlement, primarily due to its extensive lava
          tube systems. The combination of natural protection, structural
          integrity, and resource availability makes it one of the most
          promising locations for establishing large-scale human presence on
          Mars.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">Settlement Advantages</h4>
            <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
              <li>• Immediate radiation protection</li>
              <li>• Stable environmental conditions</li>
              <li>• Multiple habitat sites available</li>
              <li>• Natural structural support</li>
              <li>• Elevated communications position</li>
              <li>• Rich mineral resources</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">
              Engineering Considerations
            </h4>
            <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
              <li>• Sealing for atmospheric pressure</li>
              <li>• Access and transportation challenges</li>
              <li>• Interior lighting requirements</li>
              <li>• Emergency egress planning</li>
              <li>• Communication relay systems</li>
              <li>• Life support redundancy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-mars-900/30 rounded-lg p-6 border border-mars-600">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Primary Challenges
        </h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li>• Extreme altitude effects</li>
          <li>• Very thin atmospheric pressure</li>
          <li>• Distance from other settlements</li>
          <li>• Limited surface water access</li>
          <li>• Potential seismic activity</li>
          <li>• Transportation logistics</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Research and Exploration -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Current Research and Future Exploration
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-8 border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
        Ongoing Studies
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Scientists continue to study Olympus Mons using orbital imagery from
        missions like Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter and Mars Express. These
        missions have identified numerous lava tube skylights and mapped the
        volcano's structure in unprecedented detail.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">Research Priorities</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Lava tube mapping and characterization</li>
            <li>• Structural integrity assessment</li>
            <li>• Resource distribution studies</li>
            <li>• Geochemical composition analysis</li>
            <li>• Climate and weather patterns</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">Future Mission Concepts</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Lava tube exploration rovers</li>
            <li>• Skylight descent missions</li>
            <li>• Underground habitat demonstrations</li>
            <li>• Resource utilization experiments</li>
            <li>• Communication relay deployment</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources -->
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <a
          href="https://www.nasa.gov/olympus-mons"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            NASA: Olympus Mons Overview
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Official NASA overview of the solar system's largest volcano
          </p>
        </a>

        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martian_lava_tube"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Martian Lava Tubes
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Comprehensive information about lava tube formation and potential
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <a
          href="https://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/abscicon2010/pdf/5633.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Olympus Mons Biology Research
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Scientific paper on Olympus Mons as a primary target for martian
            biology
          </p>
        </a>

        <a
          href="https://orbiterchspacenews.blogspot.com/2021/02/first-permanent-habitat-on-mars-lava.html"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Habitat Potential Study
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Analysis of lava tube habitat potential on Olympus Mons
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>

